		{"id":"inc-d33","type":"file","file":"02 - Incidents/Incident - 2023-10 Greece D33 D35 SKELETON.md","x":620,"y":300,"width":380,"height":150,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"loc-greece","type":"file","file":"04 - Locations/Location - Greece.md","x":620,"y":480,"width":380,"height":170,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"analysis","type":"text","text":"## Reading these skeletons\n\nIf the thesis holds, the unread Syria and Greece reports should show:\n\n- Geographic clustering along Russian naval transit and air-operations corridors\n- Object profiles consistent with missiles, drones, or fast surface contacts tied to Russian or Russian-aligned activity\n- Timing correlated with KCTG transits and elevated Syria operations\n\n==Disconfirming evidence==: the small number of Mediterranean observations makes statistical inference weak. A cluster with no plausible Russian activity nearby would weaken the thesis.","x":380,"y":1000,"width":480,"height":460,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"kctg","type":"text","text":"## KCTG context\n\nThe Kuznetsov Carrier Task Group deployed to the Eastern Mediterranean in 2016 to support Russian operations in Syria.\n\nThe 18 Nov 2016 P-8A observation, 55 NM NW of Latakia, was an unidentified low, fast (~500 kt) sea-skim object passing between the Russian INGUL ARS and an unidentified vessel.\n\n==The same document that flags it as a UAP observation assesses it as standard KCTG missile activity.== The only 'unknown' was the precise launch point and missile type, not the origin.","x":-300,"y":400,"width":360,"height":400,"color":"6"}
	],
